The Laplace transform of the 3rd derivative $\displaystyle x'''(t)$ is
given by

\begin{align*}\mathcal{L}(x'''(t)) = s^3 X(s) - s^2 x(0) - s x'(0) - x''(0)\end{align*}

Plugging this into the equation, and using that the Laplace transform is
linear, we obtain

\begin{align*}0 = \mathcal{L}(x'''(t) + x(t)) = s^3 X(s) - s^2 x(0) - s x'(0) - x''(0) + X(s)\end{align*}

Upon using $\displaystyle x(0) = 1, x'(0) = 2, x''(0) = 3$, we have
$\displaystyle (s^3 + 1) X(s) = s^2 + 2s + 3$ so

\begin{align*}X(s) = \frac{s^2+2s+3}{s^3+1}\end{align*}
